Five truths about terrorism
SÃO PAULO – US policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one American in six, or approximately 16% of the population, now ranked terrorism as the top issue facing the country – an increase of 3% in just one month.
For ten years, never had so many Americans been this concerned about terrorism, although their numbers are still far below the 46% recorded following the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were most strongly felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not incendiary), certainly benefited from it.
Certain politicians justify speaking of the fight against terrorism as "World War III."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as demonstrated by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But election candidates, as well as certain media, who adhere to the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated its scale.
To put terrorism in its proper perspective, Americans should, like others, keep the following considerations in mind:
The terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists are more concerned with holding attention and dominating political news than with the number of their victims themselves.
The Islamic State (IS) pays great attention to its staging.
The barbaric decapitations broadcast on social media are meant to destabilize and shock—and consequently to monopolize attention.
To exaggerate their consequences and make big headlines with each terrorist act is to play the terrorists' game.
The terrorism is not the most serious threat facing the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills much fewer people than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be assassinated by a terrorist, according to experts, is one in 3.5 million.
The Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (one in 950,000), from an accident involving household equipment (one in 1.5 million), from a deer or elk crossing the road (one in 2 million), or in a commercial airliner crash (one in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die annually at the wheel while texting or talking on their mobile phone.
This is several hundred times more than those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War III.
The global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a wave of terrorism.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
In the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, emerging from the "autonomous" left, hijacked aircraft outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's extremist jihadis are an old political phenomenon cloaked in a religious garb.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people with an identity destroyed by globalization who seek meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
To defeat them will take time and effort, but the restrictive nature of ISIS limits its field of attraction.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIS will ultimately be defeated, just as the transnational terrorism that preceded it was.
Terrorism is like jujitsu.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat them.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in overthrowing one.
But if they manage to shock and provoke enough citizens of a state to push them into futile actions, they may hope to gain an advantage.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda managed to attract the Americans to Afghanistan.
The Islamic State was born out of the ruins of the Iraq invasion led by the United States, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, we need smart power.
Smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the military and police with the influence power (soft power) of attraction and persuasion.
The influence power is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery that the irreducibles are trying to recruit.
This is why the attention paid to the narrative of events and how U.S. actions are commented on social media is as important and necessary as precision aerial strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
The reason why some of the current presidential election candidates' anti-Islam stance is so counterproductive.
The terrorist threat is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important data point of our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap laid by the terrorists.
We do not fill the theater where the actions of thugs and hoodlums take place.
If we leave them our grand stage of public speech, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and divert our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
